HIGH|internal/debate/cluster.go:132|applyOneClusterMerge pass-2 drift recovery absorbs the SOLE unmatched record at any member location without verifying it is actually the drifted member. If a 2-member gray-zone cluster has member A match exactly (exactHits=1) and member B was refuted/removed during verify, leaving an UNRELATED finding as the lone record at B's file:line, that unrelated finding is absorbed (matched reaches 2), union-merged, and physically dropped from findings.json. The single-exact-anchor guard does not protect the second member's slot, so an unrelated co-located finding can be silently lost.|In applyOneClusterMerge, do not recover a drifted member from a location unless at least one OTHER member also matched at that same location (the same-line drift case the doc actually describes), or require an exact hit per member location before recovering its partner. Add a test: members at a.go:10 and a.go:12, member A exact, a.go:12 holds one unrelated finding, expect no merge and the unrelated finding preserved.|correctness|120|internal/debate/cluster.go:119-140|claude
HIGH|internal/debate/debate.go:255|runDebate calls applyRulings(findings, rulings) (single-finding debate verdicts: uphold/split, sets Verification.ChallengeSurvived/Notes) BEFORE applyClusterMerges folds gray-zone members. A finding can be BOTH a single-finding radar item (debated, verdict applied) AND a member of a cluster ruled merge. When applyClusterMerges folds that member, MergeJSONFindings rebuilds Verification via mergeVerification using only verdict-precedence, so the just-applied debate ruling on the losing member (ChallengeSurvived/Notes) is silently discarded.|Confirm whether a finding can appear in both rulings and a merge cluster (co-located severity_split/verification_disagreement and gray_zone can surface independently). If so, exclude cluster-member locations from rulings application, or have mergeVerification preserve ChallengeSurvived as a union rather than pick-one. Add a test where a cluster member is independently upheld before the merge and assert the survived marker is retained.|correctness|120|internal/debate/debate.go:254-270|claude
HIGH|internal/reconcile/merge.go:379|mergeVerification dedups skeptic provenance by treating each member's entire Verification.Skeptic string as one set key (seen[v.Skeptic]), but Skeptic is itself a comma-joined multi-voter list (e.g. "alice, bob"). Merging member A="sk1,sk2" with B="sk2,sk3" yields "sk1,sk2,sk2,sk3" (sk2 duplicated), and the bare "," join does not match the ", " separator other producers emit. Downstream splitNames/isVerificationTie then over-count voters and the audit provenance is corrupted. Only single-name skeptics are tested, so CI is blind to it.|In mergeVerification, split each member's Skeptic via the existing splitNames helper, accumulate individual names into the seen set, then strings.Join(skeptics, ","). Add a test with comma-joined member skeptics ("sk1,sk2" + "sk2,sk3" -> "sk1,sk2,sk3").|correctness|30|internal/reconcile/merge.go:374-392|claude
MEDIUM|internal/debate/debate.go:114|grayClusters, _ := reconcile.ReadAmbiguousClusters(reviewDir) swallows the error. A present-but-unparseable ambiguous.json returns a real error (distinct from the missing/empty nil,nil degrade path), so a corrupt sidecar silently produces zero clusters: every judge merge ruling becomes a no-op and the applied<ruled warning never fires (mergeClusters stays empty). The user is told nothing while merge rulings are dropped. The inline comment claims corrupt degrades gracefully, but corrupt is indistinguishable from missing to the caller.|Capture and log the error: grayClusters, err := ...; if err != nil { log.FromContext(ctx).Warn("debate: ambiguous.json unreadable; gray-zone merges disabled", "err", err.Error()) }. Verify with a test seeding a malformed ambiguous.json and asserting the warning fires.|error-handling|15|internal/debate/debate.go:112-115|claude
MEDIUM|internal/debate/cluster.go:50|filterMergedClusters keys idempotency solely on locationKey(File,Line). If two DISTINCT gray-zone clusters resolve to the same canonical File+Line (two ambiguous pairs at the same line with different problem text), merging cluster #1 sets a ClusterMerged record there, and cluster #2's radar item is then filtered out pre-debate and never processed even though it was never merged. The coarse location key (chosen to survive problem drift) over-suppresses; the strict no-op backstop in applyOneClusterMerge is never reached because the item is filtered before debate.|If same-location multi-cluster is possible, the filter needs cluster identity, not just location. At minimum document the limitation and add a test with two co-located clusters to decide acceptability. Verify by seeding two gray clusters at a.go:10 and confirming both get processed.|correctness|60|internal/debate/cluster.go:43-68|claude
MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/merge.go:282|MergeJSONFindings recomputes Disagreement purely from each member's scalar Severity via mergeSeverity(sf) and never reads members' existing Disagreement field. A member record is itself a reconciled record that may already carry a wider span (e.g. "LOW vs HIGH" while Severity is "HIGH"). After the cluster merge, the surviving annotation collapses to the narrower max/min of member scalar severities, silently dropping the previously-recorded lower bound, so disagreement counts understate real reviewer tension.|When building the disagreement, fold in each member's existing Disagreement lower bound (parse "<lo> vs <hi>" via the existing spreadFromDisagreement helper) and take the overall min severity across both scalar severities and pre-existing ranges. Verify with a member carrying Disagreement "LOW vs HIGH" merged with a MEDIUM member, asserting the result keeps LOW.|correctness|30|internal/reconcile/merge.go:282-295|claude
MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/merge.go:297|MergeJSONFindings copies PathValid/PathWarning/PathSuggestion from group[0] on the co-location assumption. PathWarning is file-existence-keyed (identical across same-file members) but PathSuggestion (Epic 5.4) is set only on records that went through candidate-index correction. The caller builds the group in findings-slice order, so group[0] may be the member WITHOUT the suggestion, and the merged record silently loses a valid path correction a sibling carried.|Prefer the first non-empty PathWarning/PathSuggestion across the group rather than unconditionally group[0]'s (short loop, same pattern as joinEvidence). Verify by merging a flagged member (PathWarning+PathSuggestion set) ordered after a clean member and asserting the suggestion survives.|correctness|30|internal/reconcile/merge.go:296-300|claude
MEDIUM|internal/debate/cluster.go:38|indexClusters keys clusters by FindingKey{File, Line, Problem: clusterDisplayProblem(c)} where Problem is the longest member problem; BuildDisagreements is assumed (in comments only) to use the same representative. This is an unenforced cross-module coupling: if BuildDisagreements/longestField tie-breaking ever diverges from clusterDisplayProblem's first-wins logic, the gray-zone DisagreementItem.Problem will not match the index key, the clusterIdx lookup fails, and a merge ruling silently does nothing (oc.clusterMerge stays false, never counted in the applied<ruled warning).|Extract a single shared representative-problem function used by both BuildDisagreements and clusterDisplayProblem, or add a test that round-trips a cluster through BuildDisagreements -> indexClusters lookup, especially the equal-length-problem tie case.|maintainability|60|internal/debate/cluster.go:18-41|claude
